sols_latex:
We will start by computing the Fourier sine series. The Fourier sine
series of $f(x)$ is given by

\begin{description}
\item[]
\end{description}

$Sf(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty  b_n \sin(\frac{n \pi x}{L})$\\where\\$b_n = \frac{2}{L} \int_0^L f(x) \; \sin(\frac{n \pi x}{L}) \; dx \;\;$\\for
$n = {\color{blue}1},2,3,\cdots$

Here, we have $f(x) = x$ and $L = 1$. So

\begin{align*}
b_n = 2 \int_0^1 x \; \sin(n \pi x) \; dx .
\end{align*} Integrate by parts using

\begin{align*}
u = x  \;\;\;\;\;\; dv = \sin(n \pi x) \; dx
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
du = dv \;\;\;\; v = \frac{-1}{n \pi} \cos(n \pi x) ,
\end{align*} we get that

\begin{align*}
b_n &= 2 [\frac{-x}{n \pi} \cos(n \pi x)|_0^1 + \frac{1}{n \pi} \int_0^1 \cos(n \pi x) \; dx ]\\
&= 2 [{\color{blue} \frac{-x}{n \pi} \cos(n \pi x)|_0^1} + {\color{Brown} (\frac{1}{n \pi})^2 \sin(n \pi x) |_0^1} ]\\&= 2 [{\color{blue} \frac{-1}{n \pi} \cos(n \pi) + 0} + {\color{Brown} (\frac{1}{n \pi})^2 \sin(n \pi) - (\frac{1}{n \pi})^2 \sin(0) } ] .
\end{align*} Since ${\color{Brown} \sin(n \pi) = 0 }$ and${\color{Brown} \sin(0) = 0 }$, we get that

\begin{align*}
b_n = \frac{-2}{n \pi} \underbrace{\cos(n \pi)}_{=(-1)^n} = \frac{-2}{n \pi} (-1)^n = \frac{2}{n \pi} (-1)^{n+1} \;\;
\end{align*}\\for
$n = 1,2,3,\cdots$\\Therefore, the Fourier sine series of $f(x)$ is

\begin{align*}
Sf(x) = \sum_{n=1}^\infty b_n \sin(\frac{n \pi x}{L}) = \sum_{n =1}^\infty \frac{2}{n \pi} (-1)^{n+1} \sin(n \pi x) .
\end{align*}

Next, we will find the Fourier cosine series. The Fourier cosine series
of $f(x)$ is given by

\begin{align*}
Cf(x) = \frac{a_0}{2} + \sum_{n=1}^\infty  a_n \cos(\frac{n \pi x}{L}) \;\;
\end{align*}\\where\\$a_n = \frac{2}{L} \int_0^L f(x) \; \cos(\frac{n \pi x}{L}) \; dx \;\;$\\for
$n = {\color{blue}0},1,2,\cdots$

With $f(x) = x$ and $L = 1$,

\begin{align*}
a_n = 2 \int_0^1 x \; \cos(n \pi x) \; dx .
\end{align*} When $n=0$ we have that
$\cos(n\pi{x})$=1 and so we have two distinct cases for evaluating the
integral; when $n>=1$ and when $n=0$. For the case where
${\color{red} n \geq 1}$, integrate by parts using

\begin{align*}
u = x  \;\;\;\;\;\; dv = \cos(n \pi x) \; dx
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
du = dv \;\;\;\; v = \frac{1}{n \pi} \sin(n \pi x) ,
\end{align*} we get
that\begin{align*}
a_n &= 2 [\frac{x}{n \pi} \sin(n \pi x)|_0^1 - \frac{1}{n \pi} \int_0^1 \sin(n \pi x) \; dx ] \\
&= 2 [{\color{blue} \frac{x}{n \pi} \sin(n \pi x)|_0^1} + {\color{Brown} (\frac{1}{n \pi})^2 \cos(n \pi x) |_0^1} ] \\&= 2 [{\color{blue} \frac{x}{n \pi} \sin(n \pi) + 0} + {\color{Brown} (\frac{1}{n \pi})^2 \cos(n \pi) - (\frac{1}{n \pi})^2 \cos(0) } ].
\end{align*}
Since ${\color{blue} \sin(n \pi) = 0}$, we get that

\begin{align*}
a_n = 2 [ (\frac{1}{n \pi})^2 \underbrace{\cos(n \pi)}_{=(-1)^n}  - (\frac{1}{n \pi})^2 \underbrace{\cos(0)}_{=1} ] = 2 (\frac{1}{n \pi})^2 [(-1)^n - 1]\;\;
\end{align*}\\for
$n = {\color{red}1},2,3,\cdots$

Now for the case where ${ \color{red} n = 0}$, we get

\begin{align*}
a_0 = 2 \int_0^1 x \; \cos(0) dx = 2 \int_0^1 x dx = 2 (\frac{1}{2} x^2)|_0^1 = 1.
\end{align*}

Therefore, the Fourier cosine series of $f(x)$ is

\begin{align*}
Cf(x) = \frac{a_0}{2} + \sum_{n=1}^\infty  a_n \cos(n \pi x)  = \frac{1}{2} + \sum_{n=1}^\infty  2 (\frac{1}{n \pi})^2 [ (-1)^n - 1] \cos(n \pi x) .
\end{align*}
